<https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/modifiedduration.asp> a invp:Term ;
    rdfs:label "Modified Duration Definition" ;
    schema:url <https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/modifiedduration.asp> ;
    invp:description """
Modified duration is a formula that expresses the measurable change in the value of a security in response to a change in interest rates. Modified duration follows the concept that interest rates and bond prices move in opposite directions. This formula is used to determine the effect that a 100-basis-point (1%) change in <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/i/interestrate.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">interest rates</a> will have on the price of a bond.

<span data-value="\\begin{aligned} &amp;\\text{Modified Duration} = \\frac{ \\text{Macauley Duration} }{ 1 + \\frac{ \\text{YTM} }{ n } } \\\\ &amp;\\textbf{where:} \\\\ &amp;\\text{Macauley Duration} = \\text{weighted average term to}\\\\ &amp;\\text{maturity of the cash flows from a bond} \\\\ &amp;\\text{YTM} = \\text{yield to maturity} \\\\ &amp;n = \\text{number of coupon periods per year} \\\\ \\end{aligned}">﻿<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">
